  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Defining the Application\'s Scope**\n\nI\'m focusing on defining the scope for the React app using Tailwind CSS, based on the provided \"Bildschirme, die so aussehen\" (screens that look like this). The application will be a single-page app focused on a \"LehrerPlaner\" (Teacher Planner) and the first defined screen is \"Tages\303\274bersicht\".\n\n\n**Revising Scope Definition**\n\nI\'m now refining the scope, considering the user\'s request for an app with specific screens, linked directly from HTML code. The single-screen constraint necessitates a tabbed or view-switching interface; however, the explicit instruction \"No Navigation or Sidebars\" complicates this. I\'m exploring the implications of the user-provided HTML code and the scope discipline. The user\'s goal seems to be using HTML representations to produce the application views.\n\n\n**Clarifying User Intent**\n\nI\'m now grappling with the user\'s explicit request for multiple \"Bildschirme,\" which implies navigation between views, and the conflicting instruction to avoid navigation or sidebars. The HTML provides a sidebar layout. Despite the constraint, I can utilize state-based rendering or a tabbed approach to display the 6 layouts, which includes Tages\303\274bersicht, Aufgaben, Jahres\303\274bersicht, Stundenplan, Wochen\303\274bersicht, and Dashboard, within a single-page app, using the provided HTML. I\'ll focus on extracting a layout shell and implementing a dynamic rendering solution.\n\n\n**Re-evaluating Project Complexity**\n\nI\'m reconsidering the project\'s scope. The initial assumption of a simple request was incorrect; the multiple HTML templates denote a more complex, multi-screen application. The provided HTML implies a sidebar navigation which I will incorporate. Now I need to focus on implementing a Tailwind configuration, directly using the provided color scheme, likely adding the custom colors to our `src/index.css` file.\n\n\n**Structuring the Application**\n\nI\'m now outlining the application structure. I\'ll create `src/types.ts` for definitions, `src/App.tsx` for the shell, and components for the sidebar and topbar. I also am planning individual views within the `/views` directory. Further, I have begun to extract and implement the color scheme, placing it in my `src/index.css` file to define them in my tailwind configuration.\n\n\n**Implementing Color Scheme**\n\nI\'ve extracted the color definitions from the provided snippet. Now, I will be integrating them into the Tailwind configuration. This involves adding the custom colors to the `src/index.css` file to ensure the application uses the correct color palette. I\'m focusing on defining and applying the styles as defined in the HTML snippet.\n\n\n**Integrating Font Specifications**\n\nI\'m now integrating the font specifications provided. I plan to load the specified Google Fonts, \"Hanken Grotesk\" and \"Source Serif 4,\" into the application. Specifically, I\'ll need to modify the `index.html` file to include the correct `<link>` tags for these fonts.\n\nI\'m now integrating the font specifications provided. I plan to load the specified Google Fonts, \"Hanken Grotesk\" and \"Source Serif 4,\" into the application. Specifically, I\'ll need to modify the `index.html` file to include the correct `<link>` tags for these fonts.\n\n\n**Adding Font References**\n\nI\'m now focusing on integrating the Google Fonts. My next step will involve modifying the `index.html` file to include the necessary `<link>` tags for the \"Hanken Grotesk\" and \"Source Serif 4\" fonts and material symbols, which I\'ll add after extracting the font definitions. After that, I will create some basic React components.\n\n\n**Constructing Core Components**\n\nI\'m now diving into the core structure. I\'m starting by establishing `src/types.ts` for type definitions. Concurrently, I\'ll be creating the six view components and then the application shell. I\'ve begun to edit `index.html` to include the font specifications and have started working on the `@theme` block in `index.css`, which includes `@tailwind` and the `.material-symbols-outlined` styles.\n\n\n**Defining the Custom Theme**\n\nI\'m now focused on implementing the custom theme. I will configure the application\'s color scheme, importing the provided color variables directly to ensure visual consistency. This involves creating a `@theme` block in `index.css` with the extracted color definitions, which includes `@tailwind` and `.material-symbols-outlined` styles. This will enable me to define my theme in a consistent, easily maintained location, and ensure Tailwind will recognize and use these values.\n\n\n**Implementing Color Variables**\n\nI\'m now integrating the provided color variables directly into my Tailwind configuration, specifically within the `src/index.css` file, to ensure seamless visual consistency throughout the application. I will include definitions for all the colors, to maintain consistency and ease of maintenance.\n\n\n**Defining Font Scales**\n\nI\'m now focusing on defining font scales to achieve visual consistency. I\'m extracting and translating the font definitions from the snippet, and I\'ll create variables within my configuration to represent font sizes, line heights, and font weights. I intend to use the variables extracted from the original HTML to ensure the correct font styles are consistently applied.\n\n\n\n**Defining Font Scales**\n\nI\'m now focused on defining font scales. I realized that Tailwind\'s text utilities handle line height directly, which simplified things significantly! I\'ll create custom `@utility` classes in CSS for the font styles. It\'s more manageable to create standard CSS classes.\n\n\n**Refining Font Implementation**\n\nI\'m now refining the font implementation approach. I realize that using `@utility` classes in CSS is more manageable and appropriate for Tailwind customization, due to its automatic text size mapping. So I\'ll now create custom CSS classes for the font styles, ensuring proper integration of the provided font scales.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
