  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Analyzing the Scope**\n\nI\'m focused on developing the highest-quality digital tool for Sascha L\303\274scher, Class Teacher of 6B at Schule Suhr. I\'ve begun to analyze the provided information and clarify the scope. My goal is to create a complete and perfect application.\n\n\n**Defining the Core Elements**\n\nI\'ve been consolidating the key details for the application. I now have the essential information: the school, the year, and teacher contacts. This includes Sascha L\303\274scher, the primary user, as well as the other teachers. I am taking note of their roles and subjects. I\'ve also clarified the subject abbreviations, which is important for the app.\n\n\n**Structuring the Timetable**\n\nI\'m now deeply immersed in structuring the timetable data. My focus is on representing the school subgroups, \"Gruppe A\" and \"Gruppe B,\" effectively within the application. I\'m aiming to create a user-friendly interface that allows Sascha L\303\274scher to easily switch between viewing \"Gruppe A,\" \"Gruppe B,\" or the \"Gesamtklasse\" timetable. I\'m also ensuring the timetable accurately reflects the lesson times and breaks. I am structuring the data to support a great user experience.\n\n\n**Interpreting the Data**\n\nI\'m now clarifying the meaning behind \"Montag A\" and \"Montag B\" in the timetable data. It seems these columns represent the schedules for Group A and Group B, and it\'s confirmed this by matching the class lists. I\'ve also identified instances of split lessons. I\'m focusing on \"TTG\" which represents Textiles & Technisches Gestalten frequently splits the class.\n\n\n**Verifying the Timetable**\n\nI\'m now meticulously verifying each timetable cell, row by row, using the markdown data. I\'m focusing on \"Dienstag A\" and \"Dienstag B,\" and other cells, for accuracy. I\'ve pinpointed \"TTG\" on \"Dienstag A\" and a potential error with a Chor entry in the latest row.\n\n\n**Validating the Schedule**\n\nI am now thoroughly validating the timetable data. I\'m carefully reviewing each row against the column headers to ensure accuracy. I\'ve noted that certain days (\"Montag B\", \"Dienstag B\", \"Mittwoch B\") are consistently empty. I\'m verifying the \"X\" and \"E\" entries to ensure these are correct in the timetable data for each subgroup.\n\n\n**Investigating the Data**\n\nI\'m now investigating why columns \"B\" are empty in the provided timetable data. I\'m reviewing the structure and noticing patterns. While Thursday B and Friday B show lessons in some rows, most are empty. I\'m trying to see if this is intentional or a data entry issue, and will review all the remaining rows.\n\n\n**Clarifying the Patterns**\n\nI\'m now identifying consistent patterns in the data to ensure accuracy. I\'ve noted \"Montag B\" through \"Freitag B\" are mostly empty. The structure of the timetable data is becoming clear, and I\'m validating specific cells, which I am matching against the provided markdown data. I\'m focusing on \"Dienstag B\" and \"Donnerstag B,\" as well as \"TTG\" which appears in split class contexts.\n\n\n\n**Interpreting the Data**\n\nI\'m now diving deeper into interpreting \"A\" and \"B.\" Considering the patterns, it doesn\'t seem to indicate \"Woche A\" or \"Woche B.\" Based on the provided data, the \"A\" and \"B\" seem to reference \"Gruppe A\" and \"Gruppe B.\" This is further supported by the empty \"B\" columns, which aligns with my understanding of split classes for subjects like TTG. I am focusing on matching \"A\" and \"B\" to the subgroups. I\'m verifying the patterns, and resolving these.\n\n\n**Analyzing the Implications**\n\nI\'m now analyzing the implications of the \"A\" and \"B\" designations within the timetable data. It seems the blank cells in columns like \"Montag B\" represent either whole-class lessons or days where \"Gruppe B\" is not in class. This aligns with Swiss timetable conventions. I am looking more closely at the implications.\n\n\n\n**Designing the Timetable**\n\nI\'m now designing the data structure and views. I want the app to exactly mirror the markdown table. I plan an interactive timetable view, with \"Gesamtansicht,\" \"Gruppe A,\" and \"Gruppe B\" options. I\'m creating a custom TypeScript file `/src/data/timetable.ts` to manage data cleanly.\n\n\n**Defining the Timetable Data**\n\nI\'m now writing out the teacher list, groups, and lessons within `/src/data/timetable.ts`. For each lesson, I will store the day, time, and relevant group data. I am using the terms \"A\" and \"B,\" which simplifies the column headers. I\'m checking the teacher mappings to make the application data cleaner.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will create a structured data file at `/src/data/timetable.ts` containing the metadata, groups, teacher contacts, and timetable rows. This keeps the data separate from visual components and ensures it can be reused across pages (like Dashboard, Daily, Weekly, and Timetable)."
